05085nam a22006255i 9780822386094DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223860947 a10.1515/97808223860942doi  a(DE-B1597)553896  a(OCoLC)1226680284  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aKhan, Aisha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCallaloo Nation :bMetaphors of Race and Religious Identity among South Asians in Trinidad /cAisha Khan; ed. by Sonia Saldívar-Hull, Irene Silverblatt, Walter D. Mignolo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b9 b&w photos, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations : 4600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAbout the Series -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 ‘‘This Rainbow Has Teeth’’ -- t2 A ‘‘Crazyquilt Society’’ -- t3 Locations and Dislocations -- t4 The Problem of Simi-Dimi -- t5 Carving Knowledge from Ways of Knowing -- t6 ‘‘No Bhakti, Only Gyan’’ -- t7 ‘‘You Get Honor for Your Knowledge’’ -- t8 Mixing Metaphors -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMixing—whether referred to as mestizaje, callaloo, hybridity, creolization, or multiculturalism—is a foundational cultural trope in Caribbean and Latin American societies. Historically entwined with colonial, anticolonial, and democratic ideologies, ideas about mixing are powerful forces in the ways identities are interpreted and evaluated. As Aisha Khan shows in this ethnography, they reveal the tension that exists between identity as a source of equality and identity as an instrument through which social and cultural hierarchies are reinforced. Focusing on the Indian diaspora in the Caribbean, Khan examines this paradox as it is expressed in key dimensions of Hindu and Muslim cultural history and social relationships in southern Trinidad. In vivid detail, she describes how disempowered communities create livable conditions for themselves while participating in a broader culture that both celebrates and denies difference.Khan combines ethnographic research she conducted in Trinidad over the course of a decade with extensive archival research to explore how Hindu and Muslim Indo-Trinidadians interpret authority, generational tensions, and the transformations of Indian culture in the Caribbean through metaphors of mixing. She demonstrates how ambivalence about the desirability of a callaloo nation—a multicultural society—is manifest around practices and issues, including rituals, labor, intermarriage, and class mobility. Khan maintains that metaphors of mixing are pervasive and worth paying attention to: the assumptions and concerns they communicate are key to unraveling who Indo-Trinidadians imagine themselves to be and how identities such as race and religion shape and are shaped by the politics of multiculturalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHinduism and culturezTrinidad and Tobago. 0aHinduszTrinidad and TobagoxSocial conditions. 0aIslam and culturezTrinidad and Tobago. 0aMuslimszTrinidad and TobagoxSocial conditions. 0aSouth AsianszTrinidad and TobagoxEthnic identity. 0aSouth AsianszTrinidad and TobagoxReligion. 0aSouth AsianszTrinidad and TobagoxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke Universi